* Unified deployment powered by a Node.js Express backend API, React Native Expo mobile app, a React Vite Admin panel, and Supabase (self-hosted) for identity and records

Limitations of the Study

* The system does not process actual job applications—swipe-right actions save opportunities to personal dashboard but redirect users to external sites for formal submission

* Core AI matching utilizes Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) providing deep semantic comparisons between applicant skills and live API data (Adzuna/JSearch)

* Employer validation requires manual approval by career office staff; automated employer onboarding excluded from Phase 1

* Language support limited to English and Filipino only; no regional dialect localization

* User scope restricted to Philippine residents; international job markets excluded from Phase 1

* Data retention policy automatically anonymizes all personally identifiable information 30 days post-graduation per RA 10173; raw profile data permanently deleted after 24 months

* No integration with payment gateways for certification purchases—system provides enrollment links only

* Voice transcription uses device-native capabilities without cloud-based speech-to-text services to maintain data sovereignty

All development will be conducted by the student team under the supervision of the course instructor, using open-source tools and publicly available documentation. The final deliverable is a documented, demonstrable prototype—not a live production system.

# **CHAPTER 2: Theoretical and Conceptual Framework**

This chapter establishes the scientific foundations and architectural integrity underpinning Enroute's career navigation system. Grounded in Holland's RIASEC theory and the Big Five personality framework, the platform integrates psychometric assessment with Self-Determination Theory and Technology Acceptance Model principles to ensure recommendations resonate psychologically while respecting Gen Z's digital behaviors (RippleMatch, 2023; Nielsen Norman Group, 2024). The conceptual framework operationalizes these theories into a testable Input-Process-Output model moderated by Philippine contextual realities: barangay-level commute awareness, TESDA certification integration, and RA 10173 compliance workflows. Architecturally, a multi-tier hybrid system—a React Native Expo mobile interface, a React Vite admin layer, an Express Node.js orchestration backend, and a self-hosted Supabase database—ensures institutional data sovereignty while delivering scalable, ethically transparent RAG AI guidance that addresses documented biases in commercial platforms (Akram et al., 2023; Selwyn, 2023).

## **Theoretical Framework**

This study is anchored on five interconnected theoretical frameworks that collectively explain the psychological, technological, and contextual foundations of Enroute. These theories provide the scientific basis for integrating psychometric assessment, conversational AI, and workflow automation into a cohesive career navigation system tailored for the Philippine context.

Holland’s RIASEC Theory of Career Choice forms the psychological cornerstone of Enroute’s career interest assessment. John L. Holland’s (1997) theory posits that career satisfaction arises from congruence between an individual’s personality type and their occupational environment, categorized into six modalities: Realistic, Investigative, Artistic, Social, Enterprising, and Conventional. Meta-analyses confirm RIASEC’s cross-cultural validity in Southeast Asian contexts, with Cronbach’s α ranging from 0.78 to 0.91 for scale reliability (Zhang et al., 2024). Enroute operationalizes this theory by mapping user responses to RIASEC profiles, then matching them to Philippine career pathways with documented environmental alignment (e.g., "Social" types → teaching roles at TESDA-accredited institutions). Crucially, the system addresses Holland’s "differentiation" principle by identifying dominant personality clusters rather than forcing single-type assignments—a refinement validated in recent Philippine vocational studies (Malinao, 2022).

The Big Five Personality Traits (Five-Factor Model) complements RIASEC by capturing dispositional dimensions that influence career adaptability and workplace success. Costa and McCrae’s (1992) framework—measuring Openness, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, and Neuroticism—provides granular insight into how users approach career decisions. Recent research demonstrates that Conscientiousness strongly predicts academic persistence in Philippine STEM programs (β \= 0.34, p \< .01), while Neuroticism correlates with decision paralysis during job searches (Aribe, 2025). Enroute integrates Big Five scoring (using the validated 10-item TIPI scale; Gosling et al., 2003\) to personalize Dahlia’s communication style (e.g., high Neuroticism → empathetic phrasing; high Openness → exploratory prompts) and roadmap pacing (e.g., high Conscientiousness → detailed milestone tracking). This dual-theory approach aligns with Ishchenko’s (2025) finding that combining interest inventories with personality traits increases career recommendation accuracy by 37% compared to single-metric systems.

Self-Determination Theory (SDT) (Deci & Ryan, 2000\) informs Enroute’s motivational architecture. SDT posits that intrinsic motivation flourishes when three psychological needs are met: autonomy (user control over career paths), competence (visible progress via roadmap completion), and relatedness (connection to mentors via Dahlia’s empathetic dialogue). The system embeds SDT through: (1) swipe-based filtering (autonomy), (2) skill-gap visualizations with "progress to readiness" metrics (competence), and (3) voice-recorded reflections with AI validation ("Your teaching passion aligns with Social RIASEC scores") (relatedness). This design directly counters Gen Z’s documented career anxiety; RippleMatch (2023) found that 68% of Filipino students experience "choice overload" when navigating fragmented career resources—a state SDT-based systems mitigate by structuring exploration within psychologically safe boundaries.

Technology Acceptance Model (TAM) (Davis, 1989\) guides the interface design philosophy. TAM asserts that perceived usefulness (PU) and perceived ease of use (PEOU) drive technology adoption. Enroute optimizes PU through hyper-localized outputs (e.g., "TESDA Caregiving NC II: ₱0 cost, 3 months, 85% placement rate in QC") and PEOU via Gen Z-aligned interactions (swipe mechanics, voice commands). Nielsen Norman Group (2024) confirmed that Filipino students abandon career platforms exceeding 8-second load times or requiring \>3 clicks per task—constraints Enroute addresses through offline caching and single-tap roadmap generation. Critically, TAM is contextualized for Philippine digital behavior: FDM Group (2023) showed that 74% of local Gen Z users prioritize "visual clarity over feature density," justifying Enroute’s dark-mode aesthetic with minimal text density.

Ethical AI Framework for Educational Contexts (Selwyn, 2023\) anchors the system’s transparency and compliance architecture. This framework mandates: (1) explainable recommendations ("Why this path?"), (2) human-in-the-loop oversight (counselor validation workflows), and (3) data sovereignty (RA 10173-compliant on-premise hosting). Enroute implements these through Dahlia’s "transparency layer" (e.g., "Recommended because: Your Artistic score \= 85%, matches UI Designer role requirements") and n8n audit logs tracking all AI decisions. This directly addresses Akram et al.’s (2023) warning that opaque AI career tools exacerbate bias against non-metropolitan students—a critical consideration for Philippine equity.

