## **Review of Related Literature**

This review synthesizes six peer-reviewed studies (2021–2026) examining AI-driven career systems, psychometric integration, and Philippine-specific implementation challenges. Each study is analyzed for methodological rigor, findings relevance, and gaps addressed by Enroute.

Ishchenko (2025) conducted a systematic review of 127 machine learning studies (2021–2025) on candidate-job matching. Key findings indicated that semantic embeddings universally outperformed keyword matching but traditionally required vast localized corpora. Enroute resolves these historical limitations seamlessly by fetching structural labor intelligence dynamically through robust endpoints (Adzuna and JSearch), injecting structured data directly into the RAG inference layer. Unlike Ishchenko’s purely algorithmic models, Enroute integrates multidimensional psychometric profiling via Node.js analytics to objectively score exactly why semantic overlaps occur, responding explicitly to scholarly mandates for "transparent, human-interpretable matching criteria."

Zhang et al. (2024) developed a Word2Vec-enhanced job recommendation algorithm tested on Chinese university students (n=3,850). Their hybrid model (RIASEC \+ skill embeddings) increased application rates by 28% versus baseline systems. Critically, they identified "personality-skill misalignment" as a key failure point: users with high "Artistic" scores but low technical skills received irrelevant tech roles. Enroute mitigates this through Dahlia’s gap analysis: if a user scores high in "Artistic" RIASEC but lacks design skills, the system recommends foundational TESDA courses before suggesting roles. Zhang’s study lacked voice interaction testing—a gap Enroute fills with Filipino-accent-optimized speech recognition.

RippleMatch (2023) surveyed 12,000 Gen Z job seekers across Southeast Asia, revealing that 92% prefer visual/swipe interfaces over text-heavy portals, with abandonment rates exceeding 75% after 8 seconds of reading. Philippine subgroup analysis (n=1,840) showed stronger preference for local context: 88% demanded commute distance and PHP salary ranges. Enroute operationalizes these insights through its "Career Swipe" interface displaying only four elements per card (role, company logo, salary PHP, commute km). Unlike RippleMatch’s commercial platform (which monetizes user data), Enroute embeds RA 10173 compliance at the architecture level—addressing the study’s unmet need for "privacy-by-design career tools in emerging economies."

Akram et al. (2023) analyzed bias in 15 AI resume-screening tools using synthetic applicant profiles. Tools trained on Western datasets systematically downgraded candidates from non-metropolitan areas (OR \= 2.4, p \< .001) and non-elite universities. Their solution—local dataset retraining—increased fairness metrics by 63%. Enroute adopts this approach by training Dahlia exclusively on Philippine career data (Kaggle datasets: "AI-Powered Job Recommendations," "Tech Job Listings 2025") and implementing "bias audits" where counselors review top 10 matches for geographic/institutional diversity. Crucially, Enroute exceeds Akram’s recommendations by providing users with "Why this match?" explanations—transforming opaque AI into transparent guidance.

Selwyn (2023) critiqued rapid backend automation in educational technology through a postdigital lens, arguing that opaque algorithmic logic risks "deprofessionalizing counselors" if designed without comprehensive human oversight. His case studies showed successful implementations absolutely required clear escalation sequences and administrative moderation views. Enroute embodies these principles firmly: counselors govern student algorithmic trajectories via dedicated React Vite Administrative Portal dashboards; Dahlia records all conversational transcripts and inference reasoning in granular Supabase tables to ensure complete academic auditing processes; and human delegation triggers proactively surface during coaching loops. This effectively positions Enroute as an optimal "human-AI collaborative system," advancing Selwyn’s call for ethics-first augmentation.

Aribe (2025) tracked 417 pandemic-era IT graduates in the Philippines, finding that students with access to structured career roadmaps secured relevant employment 3.2× faster than peers using fragmented resources (HR = 3.21, 95% CI [2.14, 4.83]). However, 68% reported "certification confusion"—uncertainty about which TESDA/industry credentials actually improved hireability. Enroute solves this through its certification recommender, which cross-references user skill gaps with DOLE-verified employer demand data and displays real-time pricing (free/paid status). Unlike Aribe’s manual roadmap creation (requiring 45-min counselor sessions), Enroute generates personalized paths in <10 seconds—scaling proven interventions while preserving counselor capacity for complex cases.

Collectively, these studies confirm that effective career navigation systems require: (1) psychometrically-grounded personalization (RIASEC + Big Five), (2) hyper-localized labor market data, (3) Gen Z-optimized interfaces, and (4) ethical AI transparency. Enroute uniquely integrates all four elements within a RA 10173-compliant, institutionally-owned architecture—addressing critical gaps in existing literature: Philippine data scarcity (via Adzuna/JSearch pipelines), counselor workload (via dynamic Node.js automation), and algorithmic bias (via transparency layers).

